            <div type="translation">
                <p/>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The first line appears to be smaller and more compressed than lines 2-3, which, together with the content, strongly suggests that at least one line is missing above; the layout of line 4, with an extended vacat after 'sibi' likewise suggests that only perhaps a third of the original width is preserved (restoring 'et suis' or similar). If the surviving traces of line 1 do indeed read 'BVRO', it is difficult to interpret as anything other than a rare cognomen (cf. CIL 10.640 reported in Salerno). The piece does not seem to have been recorded by Orsi in his taccuini, although observed and published by him in his first publication of material from Syracuse in 1889.</p>
            </div>
